<font color="#FF0000">PROTEST  </font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec  2 19:58:26 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I visited the Wall a little before dusk, many years ago.<br>
It spoke to me of the horrific waste of young lives for<br>
no real purpose.  The names inscribed told of the thousands<br>
whose futures ended in a far-away place, perhaps at the<br>
hand of an &quot;enemy&quot;, perhaps at the hand of an unlucky<br>
comrade.  The millions of Vietnamese, Laotians, and Tai may<br>
never have such a monument?  <br>
These names were victims of their governments policies and<br>
actions.  Not listed are the millions of other &quot;victims&quot;,<br>
whose crime was knowing and loving them.<br>
I was attending college in the Midwest at the time.  My<br>
student deferment was ending and my lucky lottery number was<br>
23.  Like many others, I would have been waiting in line to<br>
defend our country from an invader, but could not bring<br>
myself to kill Vietnamese people during a civil war.<br>
I was prepared to go to prison instead.<br>
I have never regretted my decision, even though I continue<br>
to &quot;pay&quot; for it.<br><br>
Just another victim<br>

<p><code>-- carlsong@itctel.com  (Gary Carlson) </code><p>


